In modern application development, whether using Waterfall or Scrum Agile methodologies, deployment is one of the most important stages and cannot be skipped.
Deployment is the process of distributing an application to a specific environment for testing, validation, or production use.
Deployment in Waterfall and Scrum
In the Waterfall methodology. Deployment is usually done after all stages analysis, design, development, and testing have been completed.
Meanwhile, in Agile Scrum, Deployment is performed incrementally during each sprint, allowing the team to gather feedback more quickly and continuously improve the product.
A sprint typically lasts between four and five weeks, depending on business requirements and team agreement.
During the sprint, there are several stages that must be passed:

• Sprint Planning

• Development

• Internal Testing

• System Integration Testing (SIT)

• User Acceptance Testing (UAT)

• Production Release

• Sprint Retrospective
How many deployment are performed?
There are four deployment based on each environments;

• Development Environment

• SIT Environment

• UAT Environment

• Production Environment
This means that in a single development cycle, there may be at least four deployments before the feature is actually used by end users.
How Angular could handle this?
The Angular framework provides an environment configuration feature that allows application to use difference configurations for each environment.
Here are the steps you can follow to set up your environment.
Build the environment using Angular CLI command.
ng generate environmentsBy default, this command generates environment files based on the configuration in the angular.json file, if your project is new, or if your angular.json file looks like this;
{
...
"projects": {
"your-angular-project-name":{
...
"architect": {
"build": {
"configurations": {
"production": {
...
},
"development": {
...
}
}
}
}
}
}
}By running the ng generate environments command, you will typically get two environment files.

• environment.development.ts

• environment.ts
We need three additional environment files for SIT, UAT, and Production. To generate them, update the angular.json file as shown below.
{
...
"projects": {
"your-angular-project-name": {
...
"architect": {
"build": {
...
"configurations": {
"production": {
...
"fileReplacements": [
{
"replace": "src/environments/environment.ts",
"with": "src/environments/environment.production.ts"
}
]
},
"development": {
"optimization": false,
"extractLicenses": false,
"sourceMap": true,
"fileReplacements": [
{
"replace": "src/environments/environment.ts",
"with": "src/environments/environment.development.ts"
}
]
},
"sit": {
"optimization": true,
"extractLicenses": false,
"sourceMap": true,
"fileReplacements": [
{
"replace": "src/environments/environment.ts",
"with": "src/environments/environment.sit.ts"
}
]
},
"uat": {
"optimization": true,
"extractLicenses": false,
"sourceMap": true,
"fileReplacements": [
{
"replace": "src/environments/environment.ts",
"with": "src/environments/environment.uat.ts"
}
]
}
},
"defaultConfiguration": "production"
},
"serve": {
"builder": "@angular/build:dev-server",
"configurations": {
"production": {
"buildTarget": "angular-deployment:build:production"
},
"development": {
"buildTarget": "angular-deployment:build:development"
},
"sit": {
"buildTarget": "angular-deployment:build:sit"
},
"uat": {
"buildTarget": "angular-deployment:build:uat"
}
},
"defaultConfiguration": "development"
},
"test": {
"builder": "@angular/build:unit-test"
}
}
}
}
}Run the Angular CLI command again.
ng generate environmentsNow, you should have four environments files.

• environment.development.ts

• environment.sit.ts

• environment.ts

• environment.uat.ts
Last but not least, you need to manually create the production environment file by copying one of the existing environment files and renaming it to environment.production.ts
Now, let’s update those files.
# environment.ts & environment.development.ts
export const environment = {
API: 'https://api-development.com/'
};# environment.production.ts
export const environment = {
API: 'https://api-production.com/'
};
# environment.sit.ts
export const environment = {
API: 'https://api-sit.com/'
};
# environment.uat.ts
export const environment = {
API: 'https://api-uat.com/'
};
Now, let’s validate the environment configuration by using it in a service. Run the following command to create an API service.
ng g service services/api/apiAfter the API service has been generated, update the file as shown below.
import { Injectable, inject } from '@angular/core';
import { environment } from '../../../environments/environment';
import { HttpClient } from '@angular/common/http';@Injectable({
providedIn: 'root',
})
export class Api {
private baseURL = environment.API;
private http = inject(HttpClient);
getData(){
return this.http.get(this.baseURL);
}
}
Next, let’s inject the API service into App component and display the API URL in the App component’s HTML template.
import { Component, inject } from '@angular/core';
import { environment } from '../environments/environment';
import { Api } from './services/api/api';@Component({
selector: 'app-root',
imports: [],
providers: [Api],
templateUrl: './app.html',
styleUrl: './app.css'
})
export class App {
apiService = inject(Api);
env_URL: string = environment.API;
onGetData(){
this.apiService.getData().subscribe();
}
}
<h1>API: {{env_URL}}</h1><button (click)="onGetData()">Get Data</button>
Finally, everything is set up! Now, whenever you want to run or build the application for a specific environment, simply add the configuration flag to the serve or build command.
# serve
ng serve --configuration uat# build
ng build --configuration uat

That covers the basic configuration for managing environments in Angular deployments. in the next article.
Thank you for reading, and I hope you found this article useful. See you in the next one!
